n_fft = int (0.025*f_s)     # window size (25ms). n_fft is the number of samples in 25ms
noverlap_length= n_fft-int (0.01*f_s)  # 10ms ## how many samples overlap between windows

# Compute the STFT using scipy.signal.stft
f, t, Zxx = signal.stft(data, fs=f_s, nperseg=n_fft, noverlap=noverlap_length)   # f is the frequenies, t is the time, Zxx is the STFT result

# t is spanned from 0 to len(data)/f_s (kind of)
# t resolution is hop_length/f_s, where hop_length is n_fft-noverlap_length
# f is spanned from 0 to f_s/2  (Nyquist frequency)
# f resolution is f_s/n_fft
# f formula is f[k]=k*f_s/n_fft, where k is the index of the frequency bin, k=0,1,2,...,n_fft/2

## Zxx is a 2D array with shape (frequencies, time)
## Zxx[:,0] is the spectrum of the first window
## Zxx[:,1] is the spectrum of the second window
## and so on


# lets plot the spectrum of the first window
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
plt.plot(f, np.abs(Zxx[:, 0]))
plt.xlabel('Frequency [Hz]')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Spectrum of the first window')
plt.show()

#lets plot the spectrum of the second window
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
plt.plot(f, np.abs(Zxx[:, 1]))
plt.xlabel('Frequency [Hz]')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.title('Spectrum of the second window')
plt.show()


# Convert the magnitude of the STFT to dB
magnitude = np.abs(Zxx)
magnitude_db = 10 * np.log10(magnitude/np.max(magnitude)) # in dB   #np.max(magnitude) is the reference value for dB
#magnitude_db = 10 * np.log10(magnitude/1) # in dB   #1 is the reference value for dB
print(np.max(magnitude))
##Plot the spectrogram

#print(magnitude_db[-5:-1,:])

plt.title('Spectrogram')

# def hz_to_mel(f):
#     return 1127 * np.log(1 + f / 700)


def mel_filter_bank(num_filters, nbins, fs, fmin=0, fmax=None):  ##nbins is the number of frequency bins; 
    if fmax is None:
        fmax = fs / 2  # Nyquist frequency

    # Calculate the Mel scale frequencies
    def hz_to_mel(f):
        return 2595*np.log10(1+f/700)
    def mel_to_hz(mel):
        return 700*(10**(mel/2595.0)-1)

    # Convert frequency limits to Mel scale
    mel_fmin = hz_to_mel(fmin)
    mel_fmax = hz_to_mel(fmax)

    # Mel filter bank center frequencies
    mel_points = np.linspace(mel_fmin, mel_fmax, num_filters + 2)
    
    freq_points = mel_to_hz(mel_points)  # Convert Mel frequencies back to Hz
    #print(freq_points)
    # Convert frequency values to FFT bin indices
    bin_indices = np.floor((nbins + 1) * freq_points / fs).astype(int)
    #print(bin_indices)
    #print(len(bin_indices))

    # Create the filter bank
    filters = np.zeros((num_filters, nbins // 2 + 1))
    

    for i in range(1, num_filters + 1):
        # Left and right bin indices for the triangular filter
        left_bin = bin_indices[i - 1]
        center_bin = bin_indices[i]
        right_bin = bin_indices[i + 1]

        # Triangular filters: slope from left_bin to center_bin, and from center_bin to right_bin
        filters[i - 1, left_bin:center_bin] = (np.arange(left_bin, center_bin) - left_bin) / (center_bin - left_bin)
        filters[i - 1, center_bin:right_bin] = 1 - (np.arange(center_bin, right_bin) - center_bin) / (right_bin - center_bin)

    return filters, bin_indices

# Example usage
num_filters = 20
nbins = 512 # Number of frequency bins 
fs = 16000

filters,bin_indices = mel_filter_bank(num_filters, nbins, fs)
print("Mel Filter Bank shape:", filters.shape)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
#print(filters[0])
#print(np.linspace(0, fs / 2, nbins // 2 + 1))

# Plot each filter in the filter bank
for i in range(filters.shape[0]):
    plt.plot(np.linspace(0, fs / 2, nbins // 2 + 1), filters[i], label=f"Filter {i + 1}")

plt.title('Mel Filter Bank')
plt.xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend(loc='best', ncol=10, fontsize='small')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print("Mel Filter Bank shape:", filters.shape)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.fftpack import dct
from scipy import signal

# Assuming all your earlier code is included here

# Calculate MFCCs
def compute_mfcc(mel_spectrogram, num_coefficients=13):
    """
    Compute MFCCs by applying the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT)
    to the log Mel-spectrogram.
    """
    # Take the log of the Mel spectrogram (add a small constant to avoid log(0))
    log_mel_spectrogram = np.log(mel_spectrogram + 1e-10)
    
    # Apply DCT to the log Mel spectrogram along the frequency axis (axis=0)
    mfccs = dct(log_mel_spectrogram, axis=0, norm='ortho')
    
    # Retain only the first `num_coefficients` coefficients (most meaningful ones)
    mfccs = mfccs[:num_coefficients, :]
    
    return mfccs

# Plot MFCCs
def plot_mfcc(t, mfccs):
    """
    Plot the MFCCs as a heatmap.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize =(10, 6))
    plt.pcolormesh(t, np.arange(mfccs.shape[0]), mfccs, shading='auto', cmap='viridis')
    plt.colorbar(format='%+2.0f')
    plt.title('MFCC')
    plt.xlabel('Time [s]')
    plt.ylabel('MFCC Coefficients')
    plt.show()

# Assuming the previous Mel spectrogram code runs correctly:
# mel_spectrogram contains the Mel-filtered spectrogram

# Compute MFCCs
mfccs = compute_mfcc(mel_spectrogram, num_coefficients=13)

# Plot MFCCs
plot_mfcc(t, mfccs)
